r />&gt;<br />&gt; David W has made it very clear that the eventual intent of this patch series<br />&gt; is to remove all firmware from the kernel tree and have it shipped as a<br />&gt; seperate package.<br /><br />I don't think that kind of black-and-white model is necessarily <br />attainable. Nor do I think it's even _good_.<br /><br />It's probably the right thign for _some_ firmware, assuming we have models <br />that just make it easy enough - for drivers where it's generally better <br />for distros to get the firmware from vendors rather than the kernel.<br /><br />But there is certainly nothing inherently good in forcing a split.<br /><br />I think both sides here need to calm down and stop being so extreme.<br /><br />I do want request_firmware() to be the way to load firmware (and possibly <br />other configuration data too, for that matter - I don't think it's <br />necessarily wrong for people to "misuse" it for other long-term data <br />despite the name), and I do want people to be able to update firmware <br />easily without having to force a kernel bump, but I also don't think it <br />means that firmware has to go away from the kernel sources.<br /><br />So I think the _infrastructure_ is important. But the extreme "you have to <br />split it off entirely" mindset is equally as stupid as the "you must <br />compile it into the module" mindset.<br /><br />			Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
